results.description:
Welcome to Women Who Code Mobile - San Francisco! At this week's technical workshop, we will eat, drink, mingle, listen to a lightning talk by an engineer from Minted and then we will code.

If you have interest in Mobile development, need help with a current project, or seek a supportive workspace, please attend.

Beginners will pair program with other attendees and build an app! You'll move at your own pace and will be able to get your hands dirty from initial design to full implementation. Mentors will be floating around to answer any and all questions.

----

Schedule:

6:30 - 7:00 PM - Mingle, Network and Dinner

7:00 - 7:15 PM - Welcome to WWCode & Lightening talk by host

7:15 - 9:00 PM - Choose Your Coding Adventure

----

Objective-C for iOS Development

What to do beforehand:

You will need a Mac computer running OSX 10.7 or later, with Xcode 4.5 or later. Please install X-Code from the Mac App Store before you arrive.

Learning Resources:

iOS -

>http://www.raywenderlich.com/25561/learn-to-code-ios-apps-3-your-first-app

----

Java for Android Development

What to do beforehand:

Android apps can be developed on Mac or PC. Please install Android Studio or Eclipse and the Android SDK before you arrive. If you do not have the proper equipment, don't worry, we will pair everyone up to work together.

Learning Resources:

Android -

>www.github.com/thecodepath/android_guides/wiki

----

Additional Note

This event is intended to be exclusively open for people who identify as women - we are transgender friendly.
results.name: Mobile Study Group: iOS & Android (Objective-C & Java)

results.description:
This meetup will be focused on learning the basics of C and supporting ongoing C learners. Targeted for programmers who already know at least one programming language, are excited about learning C, and would love to better understand the inner workings of memory management.

8-week series curriculum:

Part I - Introduction to the Language
2/5 - Installation, Compilers, and Hello World
2/19 - Language Basics, Part 1
3/5 - Language Basics, Part 2
3/19 - C-specific Basics

Part II - More Advanced Topics; Project **
4/2 - Pointers and Standard Libraries
4/16 - Memory Allocation
4/30 - Datatypes
5/14 - Advanced Lab

Please try to attend the early sessions if you're new to the language, as we will unfortunately not be repeating material.


Who should take this series?
* Programmers with skill in one other programming language, like Ruby.
* Programmers who need to relearn C.
* Objective-C programmers who want better C skills.
* Programmers who want to learn more about memory management.

** Curriculum subject to change
results.name: The C Programming Language

results.description:
HTML and CSS are the languages of the web, used by the billions of webpages out there today to mark up and style their content. They're also used in email marketing campaigns, blog posts, and more. If you're in the tech space or thinking of being a frontend developer, you should get HTML/CSS in your toolkit.


Want to learn how to make webpages? Already have your own blog, but want to have more control over ? This 2-day workshop is for you!

This two-day workshop will be largely
. That means that we'll start with a round of introductions and an overview of the web, and then you'll watch videos and do challenges at your own pace, using

>Khan Academy. We will stop to work on pair projects twice a day, and we'll have TAs to answer questions and help when you get stuck.


We will go from 11:45am to 6:15pm on both Saturday and Sunday, and each day will start with catered lunch.

Bring a laptop, charger, and headphones with you. If you don't have any of those, please let us know.


If you're interested in helping out as a TA, please let us know. If you recently took the HTML/CSS class, TAing can be a great test of your skills! It can also be a great way to meet other people in our community.

Many thanks to our sponsor

>Mozilla for the wonderful space and snacks.


(This workshop is half the normal rate due to there being no instructor, and proceeds from this workshop will go back to our chapter fund. If you'd like to attend but cannot afford the cost, please

Have you been learning JavaScript? Are you trying to fill in any gaps in your understanding of the basics? Join this class for an in-depth look at functions in JS. During the class, we'll cover the intricacies of scope, closures, callbacks, and more. The curriculum reinforces lectures with exercises completed on your laptop in partnership with other students (aka pair programming).

In addition to the instructors, TAs will be available to assist you as you work through the exercises.

Before class, you should already be comfortable with JS variables, arrays, objects, and loops. You should also be familiar with how to at least write and use a simple function. After class, you will have a new appreciation for the power of JS functions. You will also walk away with additional resources to continue your path to mastering JavaScript.

Find out more at

>http://www.codeclass.io
